[[File:20070204宇都宮丘陵Tagged.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The right side shows the Utsunomiya Hills.]] '''Utsunomiya Hills''' (宇都宮丘陵) refers to a series of {{ill|hills|ja|丘陵|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Utsunomiya|ja|宇都宮市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Tochigi Prefecture|ja|栃木県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, stretching northward from the central city area.
== Overview == The Utsunomiya Hills are one of the branching ridges extending in a dendritic pattern from the {{ill|Taishaku Mountain Range|ja|帝釈山脈|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Ashio Mountains|ja|足尾山地|qq=draft|qq=draft}} toward the {{ill|Kantō Plain|ja|関東平野|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="Shibuya et al. 2019">{{sfn|Shibuya, Yanagi & Seichi|2019|p=2}}</ref> Viewed from the city, the hills begin at {{ill|Myōjin-yama (Utsunomiya)|ja|明神山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, near the [[Utsunomiya Futarayama Shrine]], and extend northward through {{ill|Hachiman-yama (Utsunomiya)|ja|八幡山|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to {{ill|Tomatsuri-yama|ja|戸祭山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The foothills are flanked by the {{ill|Tagawa River (Tonegawa Basin)|ja|田川 (利根川水系)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to the east and the {{ill|Kamagawa River|ja|釜川|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to the west.
The bedrock of the hills consists of {{ill|tuff|ja|凝灰岩|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a type of stone quarried as Nagaoka Stone, which is considered a variant of {{ill|Ōya Stone|ja|大谷石|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="Shibuya et al. 2019"/> The surface is covered by layers of {{ill|loam|ja|ローム (土壌)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|pumice|ja|軽石|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and other {{ill|ejecta|ja|火山噴出物|volcanic ejecta=volcanic ejecta|lt=volcanic ejecta|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="Shibuya et al. 2019"/>
== Land Use == Due to its location within the {{ill|city area|ja|市街地|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the Utsunomiya Hills have been developed for various purposes, including {{ill|shrines|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|parks|ja|公園|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the {{ill|Utsunomiya Velodrome|ja|宇都宮競輪場|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, residential areas, {{ill|schools|ja|学校|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and cemeteries. It is also an area of historical significance, with numerous archaeological sites from the {{ill|Paleolithic period in Japan|ja|旧石器時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}} onwards. The region contains several {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} clusters, including the {{ill|Tomatsuri Ōtsuka Kofun|ja|戸祭大塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yaguchiyama Kofun|ja|谷口山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nagaoka Hundred Caves Kofun|ja|長岡百穴古墳|1=Nagaoka Hundred Caves|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Kawazuka Kofun Group|ja|瓦塚古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name="Shibuya et al. 2019">{{sfn|Shibuya, Yanagi & Seichi|2019|pp=2-4}}</ref>
== References == {{Reflist}}
== Further Reading == * {{Cite book|和書|author=Shibuya Mayuko, Yanagi Makoto, Seichi Ryota|title=Kawazuka Kofun|date=2019-03-29|url=https://sitereports.nabunken.go.jp/71238|ncid=BB28934995|doi=10.24484/sitereports.71238|series=Utsunomiya City Archaeological Survey Report No. 104|publisher=Utsunomiya City Board of Education|editor=Utsunomiya City Board of Education|ref={{sfnref|Shibuya, Yanagi & Seichi|2019}}}} == See Also == * {{ill|Haguroyama (Tochigi)|ja|羽黒山 (栃木県)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
