[[File:20070204宇都宮丘陵Tagged.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The right side shows the Utsunomiya Hills.]] '''Utsunomiya Hills''' (宇都宮丘陵) refers to a series of {{ill|hills|ja|丘陵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/hills|qq=}} located in {{ill|Utsunomiya|ja|宇都宮市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utsunomiya|qq=}}, {{ill|Tochigi Prefecture|ja|栃木県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tochigi Prefecture|qq=}}, stretching northward from the central city area.
== Overview == The Utsunomiya Hills are one of the branching ridges extending in a dendritic pattern from the {{ill|Taishaku Mountain Range|ja|帝釈山脈|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishaku Mountain Range|qq=}} and the {{ill|Ashio Mountains|ja|足尾山地|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashio Mountains|qq=}} toward the {{ill|Kantō Plain|ja|関東平野|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kantō Plain|qq=}}.<ref name="Shibuya et al. 2019">{{sfn|Shibuya, Yanagi & Seichi|2019|p=2}}</ref> Viewed from the city, the hills begin at {{ill|Myōjin-yama (Utsunomiya)|ja|明神山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Myōjin-yama (Utsunomiya)|qq=}}, near the [[Utsunomiya Futarayama Shrine]], and extend northward through {{ill|Hachiman-yama (Utsunomiya)|ja|八幡山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiman-yama (Utsunomiya)|qq=}} to {{ill|Tomatsuri-yama|ja|戸祭山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomatsuri-yama|qq=}}. The foothills are flanked by the {{ill|Tagawa River (Tonegawa Basin)|ja|田川 (利根川水系)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tagawa River (Tonegawa Basin)|qq=}} to the east and the {{ill|Kamagawa River|ja|釜川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamagawa River|qq=}} to the west.
The bedrock of the hills consists of {{ill|tuff|ja|凝灰岩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tuff|qq=}}, a type of stone quarried as Nagaoka Stone, which is considered a variant of {{ill|Ōya Stone|ja|大谷石|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōya Stone|qq=}}.<ref name="Shibuya et al. 2019"/> The surface is covered by layers of {{ill|loam|ja|ローム (土壌)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/loam|qq=}}, {{ill|pumice|ja|軽石|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pumice|qq=}}, and other {{ill|ejecta|ja|火山噴出物|volcanic ejecta=volcanic ejecta|lt=volcanic ejecta|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ejecta|qq=}}.<ref name="Shibuya et al. 2019"/>
== Land Use == Due to its location within the {{ill|city area|ja|市街地|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/city area|qq=}}, the Utsunomiya Hills have been developed for various purposes, including {{ill|shrines|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/shrines|qq=}}, {{ill|parks|ja|公園|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/parks|qq=}}, the {{ill|Utsunomiya Velodrome|ja|宇都宮競輪場|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Utsunomiya Velodrome|qq=}}, residential areas, {{ill|schools|ja|学校|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/schools|qq=}}, and cemeteries. It is also an area of historical significance, with numerous archaeological sites from the {{ill|Paleolithic period in Japan|ja|旧石器時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Paleolithic period in Japan|qq=}} onwards. The region contains several {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofun|qq=}} clusters, including the {{ill|Tomatsuri Ōtsuka Kofun|ja|戸祭大塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomatsuri Ōtsuka Kofun|qq=}}, {{ill|Yaguchiyama Kofun|ja|谷口山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yaguchiyama Kofun|qq=}}, {{ill|Nagaoka Hundred Caves Kofun|ja|長岡百穴古墳|1=Nagaoka Hundred Caves|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagaoka Hundred Caves Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagaoka Hundred Caves|qq=}}, and {{ill|Kawazuka Kofun Group|ja|瓦塚古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kawazuka Kofun Group|qq=}}.<ref name="Shibuya et al. 2019">{{sfn|Shibuya, Yanagi & Seichi|2019|pp=2-4}}</ref>
